courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate understanding in basic the definitions of algebraic structures, and in algebraic properties and their consequences for various algebraic structures;

Demonstrate ability in recognizing underlying algebraic structures which are common to various concrete mathematical examples;

Demonstrate understanding in the basics of group theory, ring theory, and field theory;

Demonstrate ability in applying basic results and techniques to solve problems in the theory and other related subjects.

Upon completion of the course, students should have

* gained an understanding in Newtonian mechanics and waves, within a formalism using vectors and elementary calculus;
* acquired familiarity with some mathematical methods, such as vector algebra and elementary calculus, gained an appreciation of their roles and applications in mechanics and the ability to apply them in other courses;
* acquired the necessary background for upper-level courses in mechanics as well as other physics courses in the curriculum;
* developed an appreciation of the quantitative nature of physics;
* built up skills for solving relevant problems; and
* acquired a sense of the importance of classical physics, especially its fundamental role in different fields in science and engineering.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate understanding in the basic notions of bilinear forms and linear groups, and basic results about such objects;
Demonstrate understanding in the basics of Galois theory;
Demonstrate understanding in the basics of module theory and representation theory, and their inter-relation;
Demonstrate ability in applying basic results and techniques to solve problems in the theory and other related subjects.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate ability in describing limit and continuity in terms of open sets in a metric space;
Demonstrate understanding in fundamental results such as Stone-Weierstrass Theorem, Baire Category Theorem and Ascoli's theorem, and apply these results in the study of theoretical or concrete problems in analysis.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate understanding in the basic notions of commutative algebra, and the basic and important results in commutative algebra;

Demonstrate familiarity with tools from homological algebra and category theory which are directly applicable in the study of commutative algebra.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate ability in defining and recognizing analytic functions;

Demonstrate understanding in the basic and important results analytic functions, and ability in providing arguments for these results;

Demonstrate understanding the important results in local and global theories for analytic functions;

Demonstrate ability in performing calculations with methods provided by the theory of analytic functions.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate understanding in the notion of smooth manifolds, and various basic concepts and constructions associated to the notion of smooth manifolds;

Demonstrate ability in performing computations concerned with various basic concepts and constructions associated to the notion of smooth manifolds in concrete situations.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:---

Demonstrate understanding in basic properties of ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations (and initial/boundary value problems involving such equations);

Demonstrate ability in applying simple analytic and geometric methods for the study of ODE’s and PDE’s (and initial/boundary value problems involving such equations), with or without finding explicit solutions.
